I think a lot about the fact that the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to critically view them.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because back then you couldn't easily determine that anyway.
We didn't question the pedestal we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency toward nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the show together.
That was completely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like it and posts social media updates with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Unconsciously, we long for this universal community that once dominated everything.
That's why so many of us still watch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," in which so many one-liners appeared that would be memes today.
We brought all these lines and assumed that most of them already understood them.
Today, you can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There's way too much, and there's no way to systematize it. Will we ever get out of this oversaturation again?
We are trapped in a cycle of constantly discovering new content, only to realize later that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must hold on to our nostalgia while at the same time accepting that the people who created the works we have liked can also have made big mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on a few toes along the way.
Now that we have lost our collective awareness regarding media, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked when he falls off.
We are in a phase of transition, and I'm curious where it will ultimately lead.
Inclusion and security should be the norm.
